 Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1118–":"about 1118–Deceased","1116–Male":"1116–Deceased","1118–Male":"1118–Deceased","1120–1153":"1120–1153","1122–Male":"1122–Deceased","1075–Female":"1075–Deceased","1125–Female":"1125–Deceased","1101–Male":"1101–Deceased","1185–1206":"1185–1206","1308–Male":"1308–Deceased","1062–1132":"1062–1132","1103–1120":"1103–1120","1132":"1132","1153":"1153","1120":"1120","1185":"1185","1075":"1075","1062":"1062","1206":"1206","1118":"1118","1116":"1116","about 1308":"about 1308","about 1118":"about 1118","1103":"1103","1125":"1125","1101":"1101","1122":"1122","1308":"1308","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","of,Monmouth,England":"Monmouth, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","of,Mynyddislwyn,Monmouthshire,England":"Mynyddislwyn, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rhydderch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Roderick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Roderick","meanings":["Welsh (Glamorgan): Anglicized form of the Welsh personal name <i>Rhydderch</i> (British Celtic <i>Rodercos</i>, presumably meaning ‘great seer’ or ‘most high’), the name of a prominent figure in first-millennium Welsh history. Compare   Prothero  ."]}]},{"name":"Gronwy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name of uncertain derivation, borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by  Goronwy the Staunch , Lord of Penllyn. He became the lover of the flower-maiden Blodeuedd and murdered her husband  Lleu Llaw Gyffes , but Lleu was later restored to life and definitively dispatched Goronwy."],"variants":[{"name":"Gronw","meanings":["Variant of   Goronwy ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gronwy ap Rhydderch was born about 1118, in Monmouth, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Rhydderch Ap Ca